    "content": "This paper presents a comprehensive empirical evaluation of the A* pathfinding algorithm across diverse problem configurations. We conducted systematic experiments encompassing 200 test cases organized into four scenarios: map size impact (10×10 to 200×200), heuristic function comparison (Manhattan, Euclidean, and diagonal distances), obstacle density effects (0-50%), and path length efficiency (distances 10-60). Our results demonstrate that search time scales exponentially with map size, increasing from 0.05ms for 10×10 maps to 1.64ms for 200×200 maps. Among the three heuristic functions evaluated, Manhattan distance proved most efficient, expanding only 40.0 nodes on average compared to 153.7 for Euclidean and 244.1 for diagonal distance. The algorithm exhibited robust performance under environmental constraints, maintaining 100% success rate across most scenarios and showing linear correlation between path length and computational cost. These findings validate theoretical predictions regarding A* performance characteristics and provide empirical evidence supporting the algorithm's effectiveness for practical pathfinding applications. Our systematic framework and comprehensive dataset contribute valuable insights for algorithm optimization and deployment decisions in real-world scenarios."
