  },
  {
    "line": 3,
    "content": "\\subsection*{Algorithm Overview}"
  },
  {
    "line": 4,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 5,
    "content": "The A* algorithm is a widely-used pathfinding algorithm that combines the benefits of Dijkstra's algorithm and greedy best-first search. It evaluates nodes using the evaluation function:"
  },
  {
    "line": 6,
    "content": "\\begin{equation}"
  },
  {
    "line": 7,
    "content": "f(n) = g(n) + h(n)"
  },
  {
    "line": 8,
    "content": "\\end{equation}"
  },
  {
    "line": 9,
    "content": "where $g(n)$ represents the actual cost from the start node to node $n$, and $h(n)$ is the heuristic estimate of the cost from node $n$ to the goal node. The algorithm maintains two lists: an open list (frontier) containing nodes to be evaluated, and a closed list containing already-evaluated nodes. At each iteration, the algorithm selects the node with the lowest $f(n)$ value from the open list, expands it by generating its neighbors, and updates their costs accordingly."
  },
  {
    "line": 10,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 11,
    "content": "The heuristic function $h(n)$ is crucial for A*'s performance. An admissible heuristic never overestimates the actual cost to the goal, ensuring that A* finds the optimal path. In this study, we implement and evaluate three different heuristic functions commonly used in grid-based pathfinding:"
  },
  {
    "line": 12,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 13,
    "content": "\\begin{itemize}"
  },
  {
    "line": 14,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Manhattan Distance:} $h(n) = |x_n - x_g| + |y_n - y_g|$, which calculates the sum of absolute differences in coordinates. This heuristic is admissible for grid-based movement with four-directional connectivity."
  },
  {
    "line": 15,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 16,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Euclidean Distance:} $h(n) = \\sqrt{(x_n - x_g)^2 + (y_n - y_g)^2}$, which computes the straight-line distance between two points. This heuristic is admissible for grid-based movement with eight-directional connectivity."
  },
  {
    "line": 17,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 18,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Diagonal Distance (Chebyshev Distance):} $h(n) = \\max(|x_n - x_g|, |y_n - y_g|)$, which represents the maximum of the absolute differences in coordinates. This heuristic is suitable for movement allowing diagonal transitions."
  },
  {
    "line": 19,
    "content": "\\end{itemize}"
  },
  {
    "line": 20,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 21,
    "content": "\\subsection*{Implementation Details}"
  },
  {
    "line": 22,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 23,
    "content": "The A* algorithm implementation utilizes a priority queue (min-heap) to efficiently manage the open list, ensuring that the node with the lowest $f(n)$ value is always selected for expansion. The algorithm maintains the following data structures:"
  },
  {
    "line": 24,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 25,
    "content": "\\begin{itemize}"
  },
  {
    "line": 26,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Open List:} A priority queue storing unexplored nodes, ordered by their $f(n)$ values."
  },
  {
    "line": 27,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Closed List:} A set containing nodes that have already been expanded."
  },
  {
    "line": 28,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Cost Dictionary:} Stores the $g(n)$ values (actual costs) for each visited node."
  },
  {
    "line": 29,
    "content": "\\item \\textbf{Parent Dictionary:} Tracks the parent of each node to reconstruct the final path."
  },
  {
    "line": 30,
    "content": "\\end{itemize}"
  },
  {
    "line": 31,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 32,
    "content": "The algorithm terminates when either the goal node is reached (path found) or the open list becomes empty (no path exists). When the goal is reached, the path is reconstructed by backtracking through the parent pointers from the goal node to the start node."
  },
  {
    "line": 33,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 34,
    "content": "For grid-based pathfinding, we support eight-directional movement (including diagonal moves). The cost of moving to an adjacent cell is 1 for orthogonal moves and $\\sqrt{2}$ for diagonal moves. Obstacles are represented as cells with value 1 in the grid, while passable cells have value 0."
