  {
    "line": 15,
    "content": "\\subsubsection*{Heuristic Function Impact on Search Efficiency}"
  },
  {
    "line": 16,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 17,
    "content": "Scenario B reveals the dramatic impact of heuristic function selection on algorithm performance. The Manhattan distance heuristic achieved the best performance with only 40.0 average expanded nodes, while Euclidean distance expanded 153.7 nodes (3.8 times more), and diagonal distance expanded 244.1 nodes (6.1 times more). This substantial performance difference validates the theoretical principle that heuristic consistency directly affects search efficiency."
  },
  {
    "line": 18,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 19,
    "content": "The superiority of Manhattan distance in grid-based pathfinding can be explained through the concept of heuristic consistency. A heuristic $h(n)$ is consistent if for every node $n$ and its successor $n'$, the inequality $h(n) \\leq c(n,n') + h(n')$ holds, where $c(n,n')$ is the cost of moving from $n$ to $n'$. Manhattan distance satisfies this property more strictly than Euclidean or diagonal distance in grid environments with eight-directional movement."
  },
  {
    "line": 20,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 21,
    "content": "Furthermore, the informativeness of a heuristic—its ability to accurately estimate the remaining cost to the goal—directly influences the number of nodes that must be expanded. Manhattan distance provides a tighter lower bound on the actual cost to reach the goal in grid-based environments, causing the algorithm to prioritize nodes that are closer to the goal more effectively. This results in a more focused search that expands fewer nodes overall."
