  {
    "line": 28,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 29,
    "content": "This robustness can be attributed to the algorithm's fundamental design. A* explores nodes in order of their estimated total cost to the goal, ensuring that it finds the optimal path whenever one exists. Obstacles do not fundamentally change the algorithm's behavior; they simply reduce the number of valid moves available at each node. The algorithm adapts naturally to these constraints by exploring alternative paths."
  },
  {
    "line": 30,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 31,
    "content": "The single failure case at 50\\% obstacle density is particularly informative. This represents a scenario where the start and goal positions were separated by a region so densely packed with obstacles that no valid path existed. This outcome is expected and demonstrates that the algorithm correctly identifies unsolvable configurations rather than entering infinite loops or producing invalid paths."
  },
  {
    "line": 32,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 33,
    "content": "The relatively stable search time across obstacle densities suggests that the heuristic function remains effective even in constrained environments. The algorithm's ability to maintain consistent performance despite environmental complexity demonstrates its suitability for real-world applications where obstacles are common and unpredictable."
  },
  {
    "line": 34,
    "content": ""
  },
  {
    "line": 35,
    "content": "\\subsubsection*{Path Length and Linear Scaling of Computational Cost}"
