  },
  {
    "line": 55,
    "content": "The efficiency of Manhattan distance stems from its mathematical properties. For any two points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$ on a grid, the Manhattan distance $|x_1 - x_2| + |y_1 - y_2|$ represents the minimum number of moves required if only orthogonal movement (up, down, left, right) is allowed. While our implementation supports diagonal movement, the Manhattan distance still provides a tight lower bound on the actual cost, making it highly informative for guiding the search."
